  "narrative": {
    "intro": "NAICS 237310 federal contract obligations for FY2026 to date total $1.5B across 1,480 awards, with an average award size of $1M and obligations up 25.7% year over year. Year-to-date totals are partial for the fiscal year. Recent fiscal-year history shows obligations moved from $1.9B in FY21 to a peak of $2.8B in FY23, then down to $1.2B in FY25 before rising to $1.5B in FY26 to date. The Department of Transportation leads buyer activity at $551M, followed by the Department of Defense at $421M and the Department of Agriculture at $420M. Vendor concentration is notable: KIEWIT INFRASTRUCTURE SOUTH CO accounts for $261M of obligations, and the next nine top vendors range from $86.3M down to $27.3M. These figures reflect current-year purchasing patterns, buyer concentration by agency, and vendor concentration among the largest contractors handling highway, street, and bridge construction work for the federal government.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How concentrated is spending among the top buying agencies?",
        "body": "Spending is concentrated at a few agencies: the Department of Transportation obligates $551M, the Department of Defense obligates $421M, and the Department of Agriculture obligates $420M. The next seven agencies together account for substantially smaller totals, ranging from $50.2M down to $428K. This distribution indicates most FY2026 to date obligations are driven by the top three buyers."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How concentrated are obligations among top vendors?",
        "body": "Obligations are concentrated at the largest vendors: KIEWIT INFRASTRUCTURE SOUTH CO has $261M in obligations, and the next nine top vendors range from $86.3M to $27.3M. The top vendor’s share relative to the $1.5B total is notable given the steep drop from $261M to the $86.3M of the second-ranked firm. AwardCount of 1,480 and an AverageAwardSize of $1M indicate many awards are smaller, while a few large contractors receive substantial portions of total obligations."
      }
